[1] Italy (Milan, Turin): waste water monitoring
Date: Thu 18 Jun 2020
Sources: Instituto Superiore di Sanita [in Italian, summarized by Pablo Nart, edited]
https://bit.ly/37J44gH
English media report: The Local https://www.thelocal.it/20200619/coronavirus-was-already-in-italy-by-december-waste-water-study-shows


The Italian Higher Institute of Health (Istituto Superiore di Sanita; ISS) reports that sewage water from Milan and Turin already contained COVID viral RNA sequences on 18 Dec 2019 [over 2 weeks before China reported its 1st cases and 6 weeks before the 1st Italian cases were detected on 31 Jan 2020. - PNP].

A total of 40 wastewater samples were collected from October 2019 to February 2020, and [compared with] 24 control samples whose sampling date (September 2018 to June 2019) enabled the presence of the virus to be excluded with confidence. The results, confirmed in 2 different laboratories with 2 different methods, showed the presence of SARS-Cov-2 RNA in the samples taken in Milan and Turin on 18 Dec 2019 and in Bologna on 29 Jan 2020. In the same cities, positive samples were also found in the following months of January and February 2020, while the samples of October and November 2019, as well as all the control samples, gave negative results.

These results are consistent with previous reports obtained from the retrospective analysis on samples of hospitalized patients in France, which identified a SARS-CoV-2 positive in a respiratory sample in a clinical case dating back to the end of December 2019, and to a recent Spanish work that found SARS-CoV-2 RNA in waste water samples collected in mid-January [2020] in Barcelona, about 40 days before the notification of the 1st autochthonous case.

The ISS results confirm the "strategic importance" of sewage water as an early detection tool because it can signal the virus's presence before cases are clinically confirmed. The ISS plans to launch a pilot study in July [2020] in the main tourist resorts and set up a nationwide surveillance system by the autumn.

Additional reading:
Daughton CG. Wastewater surveillance for population-wide COVID-19: The present and future. Sci Total Environ. 2020; 736: 139631.

A broader view, including a brief history of poliovirus monitoring, can be read here:
Sinclair RG, Choi CY, Riley MR, Gerba CP. Pathogen surveillance through monitoring of sewer systems. Adv Appl Microbiol. 2008; 65: 249.

It is also worth mentioning that in Spain, other autonomous communities are already monitoring sewage water for SARS-CoV-2 occurrence in their populations.

Valencia: https://bit.ly/37LZZbn
Galicia: https://bit.ly/3hLk4mW

--
communicated by:
Pablo Nart
<pablo.n.penalver@gmail.com>

[Thanks to Pablo Nart for flagging this study and providing other references to back this up. The information presented is very interesting, and while other studies have cited a 5% stool recovery of the SARS-CoV-2, it seems as though waste water monitoring may well be another good strategy to serve as an early alert of the presence of the virus (and infections in individuals) in a geographic area covered by the monitoring plant. One suspects that there may be intermittent shedding of the virus in stool, so single captures may have "false negative" results, but monitoring the collective waste waters in an area seems to be worthwhile. Pablo has provided background articles, including the environmental sampling routinely done for poliovirus monitoring as part of the polio eradication efforts. Positive environmental samples in geographic areas signal where teams need to go to canvas the population looking for AFP (acute flaccid paralysis) cases and flag areas that need supplemental vaccination campaigns/activities.

Looking at the 2 links for waste watering monitoring in Spain, the monitoring in Valencia has shown the amount of viral RNA detected is now approaching zero in the area. In February 2020 no virus was detected; in March and April 2020, concentrations of viral RNA were high; and in May 2020, they started decreasing and are now approaching a zero point throughout Valencia. Waste water sampling (now at 950 specimens) has demonstrated identifying the presence of virus 1 week before cases were actually detected. The Galicia report mentions they will implement the waste water monitoring in time to monitor for a possible reintroduction in autumn and to serve as an early warning system of the virus reappearing in Galicia.

A map of Italy showing regions can be seen at https://www.mapsofworld.com/italy/regions.html and a HealthMap/ProMED map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7490347,75.

A map of Spain showing autonomous communities and provinces can be seen at https://www.nationsonline.org/oneworld/map/spain-administrative-map.htm and a HealthMap/ProMED-mail map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7490347,43. - Mod.MPP]

