[Information from the Robert Koch Institute's (RKI) daily COVID-19 update adds to the above media report: "The increase in the 7-day incidence in the district Guetersloh is due to an outbreak in a meat processing plant. Several hundred employees tested positive for SARS-CoV-2. Contact tracing is ensured at the present time. The affected plant was temporarily closed at short notice and all employees are being quarantined. In addition, all schools and day-care centres in the district will be closed from 18 Jun 2020 until the end of the summer holidays (11 Aug 2020). The outbreak in Guetersloh is linked to an outbreak in Warendorf LK. Employees of the meat processing company are residents of neighbouring districts." (see https://www.rki.de/DE/Content/InfAZ/N/Neuartiges_Coronavirus/Situationsberichte/2020-06-19-en.pdf?__blob=publicationFile for full update in English).

Outbreaks in meat slaughterhouses have been reported, notably in the USA and in Brazil, and have been attributed to the close proximity workers keep in these slaughterhouses and the difficulties in working for long periods while masked. From the above report, the possibility of importation of the virus from outside of Germany is raised, but there has been virus identified within Germany that could have also been a point of introduction into the factory. According to the RKI daily report (URL listed in previous paragraph), North Rhine-Westphalia has reported a cumulative case count as of 19 Jun 2020 of 40 156 cases, the 2nd highest in the country, and 1660 deaths, with 379 cases reported in the last 24 hours and 1069 cases in the last 7 days.

The Guetersloh District, where the outbreak is located, is in North Rhine-Westphalia, in the western part of Germany. A map showing administrative divisions of Germany can be seen at https://www.mapsofworld.com/germany/germany-political-map.html. - Mod.MPP]

